{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:44:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:44:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1865"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1865"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.04,0.48,0.04,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53769"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1865"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31248"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53769"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of colicky generalised abdominal pain and distension. She has a medical history of open cholecystectomy and hysterectomy. She takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min and blood pressure 135/90 mmHg. Her abdomen is distended and soft, with numerous high-pitched bowel sounds. A plain abdominal X-ray shows numerous loops of dilated small bowel. A decision is made to treat her with intravenous fluids and gut rest. A CT scan is undertaken as part of the assessment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following CT scan findings would be most suggestive of the need for surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A transition point in the distal ileum","A massively dilated stomach","A mass lesion in the caecum causing obstruction","Thickening of the wall of the distal ileum","Gas bubbles in the wall of the distal ileum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a patient with small bowel obstruction of uncertain cause, the CT scan plays a crucial role in determining the underlying cause and assessing the viability and integrity of the intestine. A \u003Cstrong\u003Emass lesion in the caecum causing obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is the most concerning finding, as it indicates that the obstruction is unlikely to resolve spontaneously and surgery will be required. Moreover, a mass lesion at this site is most likely to be a carcinoma, necessitating urgent surgical intervention for both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransition point in the distal ileum\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the site where the obstructed and dilated intestine meets the normal bowel,but does not dictate the cause of the obstruction. While this finding helps localise the obstruction, it does not necessarily indicate the need for immediate surgery if there are no other concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emassively dilated stomach\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with small bowel obstruction and would be more suggestive of gastric outlet obstruction. This finding alone does not necessarily require immediate surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThickening of the wall of the distal ileum\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in various conditions, including inflammation or oedema associated with obstruction. While it may indicate the site of obstruction, it does not necessarily mandate immediate surgery without other concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGas bubbles in the wall of the distal ileum\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as pneumatosis intestinalis, can suggest bowel ischaemia. However, this finding on CT alone is not a sufficiently strong indication for surgical intervention, as it can have benign causes. If the patient had significant ischaemia, there would likely be other clinical signs such as peritoneal irritation or peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all these findings provide valuable information, a mass lesion causing obstruction is the most concerning and would most likely necessitate surgical intervention due to its potential malignant nature and the unlikelihood of spontaneous resolution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An unsuspected finding of a mass lesion on an abdominal CT scan should always raise the possibility of malignancy.","CT scan findings can guide the decision for surgical intervention in small bowel obstruction."],"references":["Dekker E, Tanis PJ, Vleugels JLA, et al. Colorectal cancer. Lancet 2019; 394:1467-80.","Jackson P, Cruz M. Intestinal obstruction: Evaluation and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2018;98(6):362-367. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2018/0915/p362.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1865"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-25T16:29:16+09:30","updatedAt":"202